<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
  <h2 class='text-dark justify-content-center'> Factors, Factorization and Fractions in Algebra </h2>
  </div>
  <strong>Factor</strong> is a whole number which divides exactly into another whole number.
 <br>
 
 <%= link_to "Click here for more explanation factors.", page2_path, class: "#{current? "active", page2_path}"%>
 <div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
 <h3 class='text-dark justify-content-center'>Factorization</h3>
 </div>
 To <strong>factorize</strong> means to write an expression as a product of its factors. <strong>Factorization</strong> is the process of factorizing an expression. It is simply a way of introducing brackets/parentheses to algebraic expressions. 
 <br>
 <strong>To easily factorize an algebraic expression;</strong>
 
  It is necessary to find the highest common factor (HCF) of all the terms in the expression.
  <br>
  <strong>Example 1</strong>
 <br>
 Factorize the following expressions; (i) 16x + 8y (ii) 3k<sup>2</sup> – 9k (iii) 36mn – 12m<sup>2</sup>
 <br>
 <strong>Solution</strong>
 <br>
 (i)
 <br>	
 16x + 8y; 8 is the HCF of 16x and 8y
 <br>
 16x + 8y = <strong>8 (2x + y)</strong>
 <br>
 (ii)	
 <br>
 3k<sup>2</sup> – 9k; 3k is the HCF of 3k<sup>2</sup> and 9k
 <br>
 3k<sup>2</sup> – 9k = <strong>3k (k – 3)</strong>
 <br>
 (iii)	
 <br>
 36mn – 12m<sup>2</sup> ; 12m is the HCF 36mn and 12m<sup>2</sup>
 <br>
 36mn – 12m<sup>2</sup> = <strong>12m (3n - m)</strong>
 <div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
 <h3 class='text-dark justify-content-center'>Common Factors with Larger Expressions</h3>
 </div> 
 <strong>Example 1</strong>
 <br>
 Factorize the following; 
 <br>
 (i) 2m (7n + 1) -3n (7n + 1) (ii) 10k<sup>3</sup> + 2k (r + 2) (iii) (2a + b) (5a – 3b) – (2a + b)<sup>2</sup>  (iv) (c – 3y) (d + 2) – c + 3y
 <br>
 <strong>Solution</strong>
 <br>
 <strong>(i)</strong><br>2m (7n + 1) -3n (7n + 1); 7n + 1 is the HCF of 2m and 3n
 <br>
 2m (7n + 1) -3n (7n + 1) = <strong>(2m – 3n) (7n + 1)</strong>
 <br>
 <strong>(ii)</strong><br>10k<sup>3</sup> + 2k (r + 2); 2k is the HCF of 10k<sup>3</sup> and 2k (r + 2)
 <br>
 10k<sup>3</sup> + 2k (r + 2) = 2k(5k<sup>2</sup> + (r + 2))
 <br>
 10k<sup>3</sup> + 2k (r + 2) = <strong>2k(5k<sup>2</sup> + r + 2)</strong>
 <br>
 <strong>(iii)</strong><br>	(2a + b) (5a – 3b) – (2a + b)<sup>2</sup>  ; (2a + b) is the HCF
 <br>
 (2a + b) (5a – 3b) – (2a + b)<sup>2</sup> = (2a + b) ( (5a – 3b) – (2a + b) )
 <br>
 = (2a + b) (5a – 3b – 2a – b)
 <br>
= (2a + b) (5a – 2a – 3b – b)
<br>
(2a + b) (5a – 3b) – (2a + b)<sup>2</sup>  = <strong>(2a + b) (3a – 4b)</strong>  
<br>  
<strong>(iv)</strong><br>	(c – 3y) (d + 2) – c + 3y = (c – 3y) (d + 2) –1 (c – 3y); (c – 3y) is the HCF
 <br>
= (c – 3y) ( (d + 2) – 1 ) 
<br>
= (c – 3y ) ( d + 2 – 1)
<br>
(c – 3y) (d + 2) – c + 3y = <strong>(c – 3y) (d + 1)</strong>
<br>
<br>
<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
  <h3 class='text-dark justify-content-center'> Factorization by Grouping </h3>
</div> 
Factorize the following; (i) 3x<sup>2</sup> – 6x + 2x –2 (ii) 16m – 4 + 4mn – n (iii) 6pq – 15qr – 10rs + 4ps
<br>
<strong>Solution</strong>
<br>
(i)	3x2 – 6x + 2x – 2 = 3x (x – 2) +2 (x – 2 ) = <strong>(3x + 2) (x – 2 )</strong>
<br>
(ii) 16m – 4 + 4mn – n = 4 (4m – 1 ) +n(4m – 1 ) = <strong>(4 + n) (4m – 1 )</strong>
<br>
(iii) 6pq – 15qr – 10rs + 4ps = 6pq + 4ps – 15qr – 10rs = 2p (3q + 2s) –5r (3q + 2s) = <strong>(2p – 5r) (3q + 2s)</strong>
<br>
<br>
<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
  <h3 class='text-dark justify-content-center'>Factorization of Quadratic Expressions</h3>
  </div>
  <strong>Quadratic expression</strong> is the algebraic expression that has 2 as the highest power 
  of the unknown(s) in the algebraic expression e.g. 2x<sup>2</sup> + 5x – 3. In this equation, 
  2 is the highest power of the unknown x. In term of coefficient, 2 is the coefficient 
  of x<sup>2</sup> and 5 is the coefficient of x. Remember; coefficient of an algebraic term is 
  the number that multiplies the unknown or in-front of the unknown letters in the expression.
  <br>
  <br>
  <strong>Steps to factorize quadratic expression;</strong>
  <br>
  (i)	Use the last term to multiply the first term
  <br>
  (ii)	Find the factors of the multiplication of both first term and the last term, such that if added or subtracted will give the value of the second or middle term.
  <br>
  (iii)	Replace the middle term with the values obtained in the step (ii) to make it four terms.
  <br>
  (iv)	Introduce brackets to separate them.
  <br>
  (v)	Find the factors common to the new terms in the brackets
  <br>
  (vi)	Put the factors in a bracket and place it beside one of the brackets with the common terms.
  <br>
  <br>
  <strong>Example 1</strong>
  <br>
  Factorize the following quadratic expressions; (i) x<sup>2</sup> + 14x + 13 (ii) y<sup>2</sup> – 7y + 10 (iii) 2x<sup>2</sup> – 3x – 5 (iv) 4n<sup>2</sup> + 5n + 1
  <br>
  Solution
  <br>
  <strong>(i)</strong>
 
  x<sup>2</sup> + 14x + 13
  <br>
  -	The product of the first and the last term = x<sup>2</sup> x 13 = <strong>13x<sup>2</sup></strong>
  <br>
  -	Factor of <strong>13x<sup>2</sup></strong> to give <strong>14x</strong> = 13x + x
  <br>
  -	Replace 14x with <strong>13x + x</strong> in the equation; x<sup>2</sup> + 14x + 13 = <strong>x<sup>2</sup> + 13x + x + 13</strong>
  <br>
  -	Introduce brackets to separate them;
  <br>
  x<sup>2</sup> + 14x + 13 = (x<sup>2</sup> + 13x)+(x + 13)
  <br>
  - Find the factors common to the new terms in the brackets
  <br>
  (x<sup>2</sup> + 13x)+(x + 13) = x(x + 13)+1(x + 13)
  <br>
  - Put the factors in a bracket and place it beside one of the brackets with the common terms.
  <br>
  x(x + 13)+1(x + 13) = <strong>(x + 1)(x + 13)</strong>
  <br>
  <br>
  <strong>(ii)</strong>	
  
  y<sup>2</sup> – 7y + 10
  <br>
  y<sup>2</sup> – 7y + 10 = y<sup>2</sup> – 2y – 5y + 10
 
                      = (y<sup>2</sup> – 2y) (–5y + 10)
                    
                      = y(y – 2) –5 (y – 2)
                      <br>
  y<sup>2</sup> – 7y + 10 = <strong>(y – 5) (y –  2) </strong>    
  <br> 
  <br>    
  <strong>(iii)</strong>
  
  2x<sup>2</sup> – 3x – 5
  <br>
  2x<sup>2</sup> – 3x – 5 = 2x<sup>2</sup> – 5x + 2x – 5
 
    = (2x<sup>2</sup> – 5x) +(2x - 5)
                     
    = x(2x – 5) +1(2x – 5)
                     <br>
  2x<sup>2</sup> – 3x – 5 = <strong>(x + 1)(2x – 5)</strong>
  <br>
  <br>
  <strong>(iv)</strong>
 	
  4n<sup>2</sup> + 5n + 1
  <br>
  4n<sup>2</sup> + 5n + 1 = 4n<sup>2</sup> + 4n + n + 1
  
                      = (4n<sup>2</sup> + 4n) (+n + 1)
                   
                      = 4n(n + 1) +1(n + 1)
                      <br>
  4n<sup>2</sup> + 5n + 1 = <strong>(4n + 1) (n + 1)</strong>
  <br>
  <div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
  <h3 class='text-dark justify-content-center'>Perfect Squares in Algebra</h3>
  </div>  

  <strong>In general;</strong>
  <br>
  (i)	(a + b)<sup>2</sup> = (a + b) (a + b) = a<sup>2</sup> + ab + ab + b<sup>2</sup>
  = a<sup>2</sup> +  b<sup>2</sup> + 2ab
  <br>
  I.e. the square of the sum of the two entities is equal to the sum of their squares plus twice their product.
  <br>
  <br>
  (ii) (a - b)<sup>2</sup> = (a - b) (a - b)  = a<sup>2</sup> - ab - ab + b<sup>2</sup>
  = a<sup>2</sup> + b<sup>2</sup> - 2ab
  <br>
  I.e. the square of the difference of two entities is equal to the sum of their squares minus twice their product.
  <br>
  The above is a faster method to expand perfect square expression.
  <br>
  <br>
  <strong>Example 1</strong>
  <br>
  Expand the following expressions; (i) (2x + 5y)<sup>2</sup> (ii) (2 – m)<sup>2</sup>
  <br>
  <strong>Solution</strong>
  <br>
  (i)	(2x + 5y)<sup>2</sup>   = (2x)<sup>2</sup> + (5y)<sup>2</sup> + 2((2x)(5y))
  = 4x<sup>2</sup> + 25y<sup>2</sup> + 2(10xy)
   = <strong>4x<sup>2</sup> + 25y<sup>2</sup> + 20xy</strong>
  <br>
  (ii)	(2 – m)<sup>2</sup>  = 2<sup>2</sup> +  m<sup>2</sup> – 2(2m)
  = 4 + m<sup>2</sup> – 4m
  = <strong>m<sup>2</sup> – 4m + 4</strong>
  <br>
  <br>
  <div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
  <h3 class='text-dark justify-content-center'>Difference of Two Squares in Algebra</h3>
  </div>
  <strong>In general;</strong>
  <br>
  (a + b) (a - b) = a<sup>2</sup> + ab - ab - b<sup>2</sup> = a<sup></sup>2 - b<sup>2</sup>
  <br> 
  a<sup>2</sup> - b<sup>2</sup>   = (a + b) (a - b)
  <br>
  I.e. the difference of squares of two entities is equal to the product of their sum and their difference.
  <br>
  <br>
  <strong>Example 1</strong>
  <br>
  Factorize the following; (i)  n<sup>2</sup> – 16 (ii) 9x<sup>2</sup> – 4y<sup>2</sup> (iii) 25 – 36h<sup>2</sup> (iv) 13<sup>2</sup> -  12<sup>2</sup>
  <br>
  <strong>Solution</strong>
  <br>
  (i)	n<sup>2</sup> – 16 = n<sup>2</sup> – 4<sup>2</sup> = <strong>(n + 4) (n – 4)</strong>
  <br> 
