  <hr>
  <article>
  <strong>Algebra</strong> is the branch of mathematics that deals with symbols and the operations for manipulating those symbols.
  <div class="d-flex justify-content-center mt-3">
  <h2 class='text-dark justify-content-center'>Identifying Coefficient in Algebraic Expression</h2>
  </div>
  <strong>Coefficient</strong> is a number multiplying an algebraic letter or a number in-front of an algebraic letter. It could be a whole number or a fraction.
  <br>
  <strong class='ml-4'>Example 1</strong>
  <br>
  <%= image_tag 'coefficient.png', alt:'coefficient', class: 'carol' %>
  <div class="d-flex justify-content-center mt-3">
  <h3 class='text-dark justify-content-center'>Arranging Positive and Negative terms together in Algebra</h3>
  </div>
  This involves putting together all the elements with similar signs i.e. positive <strong>(+)</strong> term with positive <strong>(+)</strong> term and negative <strong>(-)</strong> term with negative <strong>(-)</strong> term.
  <br>
  <strong>Example 1</strong>
  <br>
  Simplify the following algebraic expressions (i) 3k – 5k – 4k + 10k (ii) 10y – 3y + 4y – 22y + 13y
  <br>
  <strong>Solution</strong>
  <br>
  (i)	3k – 5k – 4k + 10k = 3k + 10k – 5k – 4k = 13k – 9k = <strong>4k</strong>
  <br>
  (ii)	10y – 3y + 4y – 22y + 13y =  10y + 4y + 13y – 3y – 22y = 27y – 25y = <strong>2y</strong>
  <div class="d-flex justify-content-center mt-3">
  <h3 class='text-dark justify-content-center'>Grouping Like and Unlike Terms in Algebra</h3>
  </div>
  This involves arrangement of elements in <strong>like terms</strong> (elements with the same algebraic letters) and <strong>unlike terms</strong> (elements with different algebraic letters) patterns.
  <br>
  <strong>Example 1</strong>
  <br>
  Simplify the following algebraic expressions; (i) 2 + 8x + 5y – 3x –2y (ii) 9k + 3u – 4k –3u –7k + 5k
  <br>
  Solution
  (i)	2 + 8x + 5y – 3x -2y = 8x - 3x +5y – 2y + 2 = <strong>5x + 3y + 2</strong>
  <br>
  (ii)	9k + 3u – 4k – 3u – 7k + 5k = 9k + 5k – 4k – 7k + 3u – 3u = 14k – 11k + 0 = <strong>3k</strong>
  <div class="d-flex justify-content-center mt-3">
  <h2 class='text-dark justify-content-center'>Multiplication and Division in Algebraic Expressions</h2>
  </div>
  <div class="d-flex justify-content-center mt-3">
  <h3 class='text-dark justify-content-center'>Multiplication in Algebraic Expressions</h3>
  </div>
  This involves the use of coefficients in the algebraic multiplication process.
  <br>
  <strong>Example 1</strong>
  <br>
  Simplify the following expressions (i) 3y x 4 (ii) 6 x 2m (iii) 8a x 3a (iv) 2 x 4ny (v) 12ab x 3b (v) k x 15ky.
  <br>
  <strong>Solution</strong>
  (i)	3y x 4 = 3 x 4 x y = <strong>12y</strong>
  <br>
  (ii)	6 x 2m = 6 x 2 x m = <strong>12m</strong>
  <br>
  (iii)	8a x 3a = 8 x 3 x a x a = <strong>24a<sup>2</sup></strong>
  <br>
  (iv)	2 x 4ny = 2 x 4 x n x y = <strong>8ny</strong>
  <br>
  (v)	12ab x 3b = 12 x 3 x a x b x b = <strong>36ab<sup>2</sup></strong>
  <br>
  (vi)	k x 15ky = 15 x k x k x y = <strong>15k<sup>2</sup>y</strong>
  <div class="d-flex justify-content-center mt-3">
  <h3 class='text-dark justify-content-center'>Division in Algebraic Expressions</h3>
  </div>
  <strong>This involves division of the coefficients in the algebraic expressions.</strong>
  <br>
  <strong>Example 1</strong>
  <br>
  Simplify the following expressions; (i) <sup>8b</sup>&frasl;<sub>4</sub> (ii) 36a<sup>2</sup>y ÷ 6ay (iii) k<sup>2</sup> ÷ k 
  <br>
  <strong>Solution</strong>
  <br>
  <%= image_tag 'divSolution.png', alt:'division of fractions', class: 'carol' %>
  <div class="d-flex justify-content-center mt-3">
  <h3 class='text-dark justify-content-center'>Order of Operations in Algebra</h3>
  </div>
  The order of operations in mathematics can be easily resolved using <strong>BODMAS</strong> or <strong>PEMDAS</strong>. 
  <br>
  In <strong>BODMAS</strong>; <strong>B</strong> => Brackets, <strong>O</strong> => Order, <strong>D</strong> = Division, <strong>M</strong> => Multiplication, <strong>A</strong> => Addition and <strong>S</strong> => Subtraction. 
  <br>
  O is (of) in some countries.
  <br>
  In <strong>PEMDAS</strong>; <strong>P</strong> => Parentheses, <strong>E</strong> = Exponents, <strong>M</strong> => Multiplication, <strong>D</strong> = Division, <strong>A</strong> => Addition and <strong>S</strong> => Subtraction.
  <br>
  <strong>The order of operations rules in algebraic expressions;</strong>
  <br>
  (i)	If there are no brackets/parentheses, do multiplication or division before addition or subtraction.
  <br>
  (ii)If there are brackets/parentheses, do the operations in the brackets/parentheses first.
  <br>
  <%= link_to "Click here for more information on BODMAS/PEMDAS and the order of operations.", page3_path, class: "#{current? "active", page3_path}"%>
  <br>
  <strong>Example 1</strong>
  <br>
  Solve the following expressions; (i) 14 x 3 – 2 + 12 ÷ 6 (ii) 6 x 2n – (4n + 3n) x 3 (iii) 8y + 12y ÷ 6 (iv) 21k ÷ 7 + 6k + 2 x 3k.
  <br>
  <strong>Solution</strong>
  <br>
  This can be solved using BODMAS/PEMDAS;
  <br>
  (i)	<strong>14 x 3 – 2 + 12 ÷ 6 </strong>= (14 x 3) – 2 + (12 ÷ 6) = 42 –2 + 2 = 42 + 2 – 2 = 44 – 2 = <strong>42</strong>
  <br>
  (ii) <strong>6 x 2n – (4n + 3n) x 3</strong> = (6 x 2n) – (4n + 3n) x 3  = 12n – 7n x 3 = 12n – 21n = <strong>-9n</strong>
  <br>
  (iii) <strong>8y + 12y ÷ 6</strong> = 8y + (<sup>12y</sup>&frasl;<sub>6</sub>) = 8y + 2y = <strong>10y</strong>
  <br>
  (iv) <strong>21k ÷ 7 + 6k + 2 x 3k</strong>  =  (<sup>21k</sup>&frasl;<sub>7</sub>) + 6k + (2 x 3k) = 3k + 6k + 6k = 9k + 6k = <strong>15k</strong>
  <br>
  <br>
  <div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
    <h3 class='text-dark justify-content-center'> Removing Brackets in Algebraic Expression </h3>
  </div>
  This is the process of eliminating brackets from algebraic expressions, thereby exposing the terms to one another.
  <div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
  <h3 class='text-dark justify-content-center'>Positive Sign (+) before the Bracket</h3>
  </div>
  If the sign before the bracket is positive (+), the signs of the terms inside the bracket remain the same when the bracket/parenthesis is removed.
  <br>
  <strong>Note:</strong> just remove the bracket if there is no sign before the first bracket.
  <br>
  <strong>Example 1</strong>
  <br>
  Simplify the following; (i) 8y + (4k + 2y) (ii) 10m + (5m – 6n) (iii) (12r – 8m) + (7r – 4m) 
  <br>
  <strong>Solution</strong>
  <br>
  (i)	<strong>8y + (4k + 2y)</strong> = 8y + 4k + 2y = 8y + 2y + 4k = <strong>10y + 4k</strong>
  <br>
  (ii)	<strong>10m + (5m – 6n)</strong> = 10m + 5m – 6n = <strong>15m – 6n</strong>
  <br>
  (iii)	<strong>(12r – 8m) + (7r – 4m)</strong> =  12r – 8m + 7r – 4m = 12r + 7r – 8m – 4m = <strong>19r –12m</strong>
  <br>
  <br>
  <div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
  <h3 class='text-dark justify-content-center'>Negative Sign (–) before the Bracket</h3>
  </div>
  If the sign before the bracket is negative (–), the signs of the terms inside the bracket will change to the opposite signs when the bracket/parenthesis is removed i.e. if positive (+) it will change to negative (-) vice versa.
  <br>
  <strong>Example 2</strong>
  <br>
  Simplify the following algebraic expressions; (I) 7b – (5b + 2) (ii) 20n – (3m –3n + 2) (iii) (4y – x) – (5x – 3y)
  <br>
  <strong>Solution</strong>
  <br>
  (i)	<strong>7b – (5b + 2)</strong> = 7b – 5b – 2 = <strong>2b – 2</strong>
  <br>
  (ii)<strong>20n – (3m –3n + 2)</strong> = 20n – 3m +3n – 2 = 20n + 3n – 3m – 2 = <strong>23n – 3m – 2</strong>
  <br>
  (iii)<strong>(4y – x) – (5x – 3y)</strong> = 4y – x – 5x + 3y = 4y + 3y – 5x – x  = <strong>7y – 6x</strong> 
  <br>
  <strong>Example 3</strong>
  <br>
  Simplify the following by removing the brackets; 
  <br>
  (i) 5(2m – n) (ii) –4p (3q + 2) (iii) (–5x + y) (–9y) (iv) k (4a + 3) + 5(a + 2) (v) 3 (2x – y) –2(3x – 4y)
  <br>
  <strong>Solution</strong>
  <br>
  (i)	5(2m – n) = <strong>10m – 5n</strong>
  <br>
  (ii)	–4p (3q + 2) = –12pq – 8p
  <br>
  (iii)	(–5x + y) (–9y) = –9y (–5x + y) = <strong>45xy – 9y<sup>2</sup></strong>
  <br>
  (iv)	k (4a + 3) + 5(a + 2) = <strong>4ak + 3k + 5a + 10</strong>
  <br>
  (v)	3(2x – y) –2(3x – 4y) = 6x – 3y – 6x + 8y = 6x – 6x + 8y – 3y = 0 + 5y = <strong>5y</strong>
  <br>
  <br>
  <div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
    <h3 class='text-dark justify-content-center'> Expansion in Algebra </h3>
  </div>
  <strong>Expansion</strong> means to remove or open up the brackets in algebraic expressions. When two terms are involved, it is called <strong>binomial</strong>, three terms means <strong>trinomial</strong>.
  <br>
  <strong>In binomial;</strong>
  <br>
  (i)	The first bracket is open up to be able the use the terms inside it.
  <br>
  (ii)	Each term in the first bracket is used to multiply the terms inside the second bracket appropriately.
  <br>
